aI: 0.37; aII: 0.21; aIII: 0.26; aIV: 0.4; aV: 0.42; aVI: 0.45; aVII: 0.45; aVIII: 0.42; aIX: 0.41; aX: 0.39; aXI: 0.44
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C331F4EFFFD91D435053FAF1FC96FAEC" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B94A764FFD91D435053FAF1FC96FAEC" blockId="7.[94,718,1306,1395]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D435053FAF1FD9BFAAC" bold="true" box="[94,230,1306,1331]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derivative of the Latin words 
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D4350A7FAD1FD97FACC" box="[170,234,1338,1363]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">luteus</emphasis>
(yellow) + 
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D435164FAD1FCC7FACC" box="[361,442,1338,1363]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">apicalis</emphasis>
(apex), referring to their yellow patches in the apex of elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C331F4EFFFD91D435053FA71FC29F7CC" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B94A764FFD91D435053FA71FFD9FA2C" blockId="7.[94,676,1434,1459]" box="[94,676,1434,1459]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D435053FA71FD8BFA2C" bold="true" box="[94,246,1434,1459]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Distribution:</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="F33CE7F4FFD91D4350F6FA71FC4AFA2C" box="[251,311,1434,1459]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="49EF6986FFD91D43514EFA71FF73FA2C" box="[323,526,1434,1459]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Mato Grosso state</collectingRegion>
) (
<figureCitation id="1310BBE1FFD91D435212FA71FFE7FA2C" box="[543,666,1434,1459]" captionStart="Figures 66-69" captionStartId="19.[94,162,2042,2067]" captionTargetBox="[151,1360,431,2012]" captionTargetId="figure-79@19.[151,1360,431,2012]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figures 66-69: Distribution of Macromalthinus species. (66) Distribution of Macromalthinus species in South America. (67) Distribution of M. brasiliensis in Brazil.(68)Distribution ofM.maximiceps inFrench Guiana.(69)Distribution of M.guyanensis sp.nov.,andM.orapuensis sp.nov.inFrench Guiana.Background maps of Figs.66-67 by NaturalEarth (available at:www.naturalearthdata.com), and Figs.68-69 byEric Gaba." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384172" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384172/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figs. 66-67</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B94A764FFD91D435053FA31FC29F7CC" blockId="7.[94,719,1498,2131]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D435053FA31FC25FA6C" bold="true" box="[94,344,1498,1523]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Locality description:</emphasis>
The specimens were collected during an expedition held by the joint Royal Society &amp; Royal Geographical Society (
<collectingCountry id="F33CE7F4FFD91D4351ACF9F1FF23F9AC" box="[417,606,1562,1587]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">United Kingdom</collectingCountry>
) sponsorship in cooperation with the National Research Council of 
<collectingCountry id="F33CE7F4FFD91D435070F9B1FDC4F9EC" box="[125,185,1626,1651]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Brazil</collectingCountry>
during 1967 and 1969. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBADA95FFD91D4351C5F9B1FF20F9EC" author="Brown, E. H." box="[456,605,1626,1651]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="365 - 367" refId="ref18525" refString="Brown, E. H. 1970. Introduction. Geographical Research on the Royal Society / Royal Geographical Society's Expedition to North-Eastern Mato Grosso, Brazil: A Symposium. [Brown, E. H.; Askew, G. P.; Thornes, J. B.; Young, A.; Townshend, J. R. G. &amp; Daultrey, S. G. Eds.]. The Geographical Journal, 136 (3): 365 - 367." type="journal article" year="1970">Brown (1970)</bibRefCitation>
describes the vegetation near the base camp, where the specimens were collected, as:“forest (
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D4351CCF971FC86F92C" box="[449,507,1690,1715]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">mata</emphasis>
), savanna (
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D435278F971FFBAF92C" box="[629,711,1690,1715]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">cerrado</emphasis>
) and grassland (
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D435105F951FC2FF94C" box="[264,338,1722,1747]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">campo</emphasis>
). The base camp was located near the southern boundary of the Amazonian mata, where, on the interfluves, close-canopied dry forest gives way to woodland cerrado, usually through a short transition of cerradão, a taller denser form of cerrado. In the valleys gallery forest follows the stream sides in both cerrado and dry forest. Campos, varying from shrub-free grassland (
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D435092F871FC52F82C" box="[159,303,1946,1971]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">campo limpo</emphasis>
), to grasslands with occasional trees (
<emphasis id="B95F7B76FFD91D43506BF851FD98F84C" box="[102,229,1978,2003]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">campo sujo</emphasis>
), characterize valley slopes in the cerrado where soils are saturated in the wet season”. Fifty years later, little remains of the original vegetation, since the area is currently threatened by deforestation, extensive farming and livestock.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
